ray}} When Jade, Jack, and Jackiey entered the house they became \"masters\" along with Jermaine, Ken, and Shilpa. The other eight housemates were chosen to be their \"servants\" and moved to the House Next Door. It was revealed that the masters are automatically nominated for eviction in which the viewers are to vote which housemates to save, rather than evicted. Therefore, the housemate with the fewest votes is evicted. Donny, who was originally a servant, left the house on Day 3. On Day 5, Ken voluntarily left after being involved in arguments with housemates. The eviction was not cancelled, and Ken's number was removed from the voting system.\n*{{note|2|Note 2}}: Carole and Cleo were banned from nominating as a punishment for discussing nominations earlier. Additionally, housemates had to choose one of them to face the public vote.<ref>\"[http://bigbrother.digitalspy.co.uk/article/ds11203.html Housemates to nominate today] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113101944/http://bigbrother.digitalspy.co.uk/article/ds11203.html |date=13 January 2007 }}\", ''Digital Spy''. Retrieved 11 January 2007.</ref> They chose Carole.<ref>\"[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1174&articleMask=1&housemateId= The Punishment Fits the Crime]\", ''Channel Four's Official Big Brother Website''. Retrieved 11 January 2007.</ref> On Day 10, Leo escaped the house. The eviction was not cancelled, and Leo's number was removed from the voting system.\n*{{note|3|Note 3}}: The nominations were cast on Day 15 and announced on Day 16. The voting package was delayed and only shown at the end of ''Big Brother's Big Mouth'' where it was also revealed that all Channel 4's profits for this vote will go to charity.\n*{{note|4|Note 4}}: There was a double eviction on Day 24 and therefore the three or more housemates were placed up for the public vote rather than the two or more housemates. If there was not a double eviction, Dirk and Jo would have faced the public vote. The voting lines originally opened on Day 22 but were reset on Day 23 due to an error which stated that viewers were to vote to save [[Shilpa Shetty|Shilpa]] when they were in fact voting to evict. Viewers who had voted before the lines were reset were offered a full refund with all unclaimed money and profits from the vote being donated to charity<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1404&articleMask=1 Voting Reset & Refund Information] ''Channel Four's Official Big Brother Website''. Retrieved 26 January 2007</ref>\n*{{note|5|Note 5}}: There were no nominations in the final two days and instead the public were voting for the housemate they wanted to win rather than evict. There was a double eviction on Day 24, two days before the final.\n</small>\n\n===Voting fault===\nOne event in this series was a technical fault that affected voting lines in the eviction between [[Cleo Rocos]], [[Dirk Benedict]], [[Ian \"H\" Watkins|Ian Watkins]], Jo O'Meara and Shilpa Shetty. Everyone who voted was offered a refund.  Any unclaimed money would be donated to charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6279363.stm|title=Are housemates aware of race row?|date=19 January 2007|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 January 2007|first=Mark|last=Savage}}</ref><ref name=\"no crowd no shock\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_headline=no-crowd-no-shock%2D%2D-no-reality%26method=full%26objectid=18505500%26siteid=94762-name_page.html|title=NO CROWD NO SHOCK.. NO REALITY|date=20 January 2007|work=Daily Mirror|accessdate=20 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Viewership==\nAll viewing figures below are provided by the [[Broadcasters Audience Research Board]] (or \"BARB\").<ref name=\"BARB\">{{Cite url|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30|title=Weekly top 30 programmes|publisher=[[Broadcasters Audience Research Board]]|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; width: 50%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"|\n! scope=col colspan=5| Official viewers (millions)\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Week 1\n! Week 2\n! Week 3\n! Week 4\n|-\n! Saturday\n| style=\"background:#ccc;\" rowspan=\"4\" | || 3.16 || 2.93 || 3.30 || 2.56\n|-\n! Sunday\n| 3.39 || 3.03 || 3.65 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 6.01\n|-\n! Monday\n| 3.81 || 3.75 || 4.16 ||style=\"background:#ccc;\" rowspan=\"6\" |\n|-\n! Tuesday\n| 4.10 || 4.72 || 4.32 \n|-\n! Wednesday\n| style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 7.32 || 4.51 || 5.40 || 4.71 \n|-\n! Thursday\n| 5.48 || 3.72 || 5.89 || 4.47\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Friday\n| style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 4.25 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 3.50 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 7.61 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 5.14\n|-\n| style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 5.27 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 3.80 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 8.78 || style=\"background:#87CEFA;\" | 5.26\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FADADD;\" |\n! Weekly average\n| colspan=\"2\" | 4.36 || 5.26 || 4.36 || 4.29\n|- style=\"background:#EEDC82;\" |\n! Running average\n| colspan=\"2\" | 4.36 || 4.81 || 4.66 || 4.57\n|- style=\"background:#ADDFAD;\" |\n! Series average\n| colspan=\"6\" | 4.6\n|-\n| colspan=6|<small>''[[Azure (color)#Light sky blue|blue-coloured]] boxes denote live shows.''</small>\t\n|}\n\n==Racism controversy==\n{{main|Celebrity Big Brother racism controversy}}\n''Celebrity Big Brother'' criticism focused around the treatment of housemate [[Shilpa Shetty]] by contestants [[Jade Goody]], [[Jo O'Meara]] and [[Danielle Lloyd]].\nUK media regulator [[Ofcom]] received more than 44,500 complaints<ref name=\"Ofcom report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ofcom.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/61404/channel4_cbb.pdf|title=Adjudication of Ofcom Content Sanctions Committee - Channel Four Television Corporation in respect of its service Channel 4|date=2007-05-24|publisher=[[Ofcom]]|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref> \u2013 a record number for a British television programme after transmission. [[Channel 4]] received an additional 3,000 complaints,<ref name=\"Guardian diplomatic incident\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jan/18/bigbrother.politics|title=Racism, ratings and reality TV: now Big Brother creates a diplomatic incident|first1=Owen|last1=Gibson|first2=Vikram|last2=Dodd|first3=Randeep|last3=Ramesh|date=2007-01-18|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"Ofcom-complaints\">\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6272585.stm Channel 4 denies Brother 'racism']\", BBC News. Retrieved 17 January 2007.</ref> about racism and [[bullying]] by housemates against Shetty. The [[Eastern Eye (newspaper)|Eastern Eye]] newspaper launched an online petition that registered over 30,000 signatures.<ref>\"[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/foreignaffairs/story/0,,1992924,00.html Racism, ratings and reality TV]\", ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 18 January 2007</ref> Channel 4, who had initially described the situation as \"girly rivalry\", later admitted there had \"undoubtedly been a cultural clash between her and three of the British females in the house\".<ref name=\"Shetty fears Big Brother 'racism'\">{{cite news|publisher=BBC News| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6273677.stm|title=Shetty fears Big Brother 'racism'|date=18 January 2007|accessdate=28 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter an investigation by Ofcom, they concluded that Channel 4 had breached the [[Broadcasting Code]] on three separate occasions.<ref name=\"Ofcom report\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/ ''Celebrity Big Brother''] at [[Channel4.com]]\n* {{IMDb title|0279550|Celebrity Big Brother}}\n{{coord|51|39|23|N|0|16|02|W|display=title}}\n{{Big Brother UK}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Celebrity Big Brother 2007 (Uk)}}\n[[Category:2007 British television seasons]]\n[[Category:Celebrity Big Brother (British TV series) seasons|05]]\n[[Category:Channel 4 reality television programmes]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the UK television series|other uses|Celebrity Big Brother}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 5\n| bgcolour             = #fada00<!-- Colours used must meet the contrast requirements of WP:COLOR. -->\n| image                = Celebrity Big Brother 2007 (UK) logo.png\n| caption              = Series five logo\n| module1              = {{Infobox reality competition season\n| presenter            = [[Davina McCall]]\n| num_days             = 26\n| num_housemates       = 14\n| winner               =[[Shilpa Shetty]]\n| runner_up            = [[Jermaine Jackson]]\n| companion_shows      = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[List of Big Brother (UK) shows#Big Brother's Little Brother|Big Brother's Little Brother]]''\n* ''[[List of Big Brother (UK) shows#Big Brother's Big Mouth|Big Brother's Big Mouth]]''\n* ''[[List of Big Brother (UK) shows#Big Brother's Big Brain|Big Brother's Big Brain]]''\n* ''[[List of Big Brother (UK) shows#Big Brother Live|Big Brother Live]]''\n* ''[[List of Big Brother (UK) shows#Diary Room Uncut|Diary Room Uncut]]''\n}}\n}}\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| num_episodes         = 30\n| network              = [[Channel 4]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2007|01|03|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2007|01|28|df=y}}\n}}\n'''''Celebrity Big Brother 2007''''', also known as '''''Celebrity Big Brother 5''''', was the fifth series of the British [[reality television]] series ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (British TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]]''. The show followed a total of [[Celebrity Big Brother 5 (UK)#Housemates|fourteen]] [[celebrity]] contestants, known as housemates, who were isolated from the outside world for an extended period of time in a custom built House. Each week, one or more of the housemates were eliminated from the competition by public vote and left the House. The last remaining housemate, [[Shilpa Shetty]], was declared the winner and she received \u00a3100000.\n\nThe series launched on [[Channel 4]] on 3 January 2007 and ended on 28 January 2007. [[Davina McCall]] returned as presenter, having presented both the [[Big Brother (UK)|regular]] edition and the celebrity edition of ''Big Brother'' since they first began. Eleven housemates entered on launch night, with an additional three being introduced two days later. The series was watched by an average of 4.6 million viewers, the third highest viewed series of the show to date. As with the previous [[Big Brother 7 (UK)|regular series]], it was broadcast in [[16:9]] aspect ratio, as opposed to [[4:3]] \u2013 the first series of ''Celebrity Big Brother'' to do so.\n\nThe series saw the return of [[Jade Goody]], who had become a media celebrity after appearing on the [[Big Brother 3 (UK)|third regular series]] of ''Big Brother'' in 2002, arriving with her boyfriend and her mother \u2013 marking the first time in any series of ''Big Brother UK'' where family members entered together. During its original broadcast, ''Celebrity Big Brother 5'' had become the subject of an internationally publicised [[Celebrity Big Brother racism controversy|racism controversy]]. It attracted the largest number of complaints to the UK media regulator [[Ofcom]] about a ''Big Brother'' series and, as of 2018, the second highest number of complaints about any British television broadcast of all time (after ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera]]''). Viewer complaints and press attention concerned housemate [[Shilpa Shetty]], and alleged that she was the subject of [[racism|racist]] [[bullying]] from some of her fellow housemates, in particular Jade Goody, [[Danielle Lloyd]] and [[Jo O'Meara]]. As a result, a protest took place in [[India]]; tensions increased between the UK and Indian governments; and a [[diplomatic incident]] occurred. Following the broadcast of the series, Ofcom concluded that ''Celebrity Big Brother 5'' had breached the [[Broadcasting Code]], and statutory sanctions were placed on Channel 4.\n\n==Production==\n===Eye logo===\nThe eye logo for this series was the same yellow and black spiraled eye used for [[Big Brother 7 (UK)|Big Brother 7]]. Two modifications were a black background, therefore camouflaging the black spiral in the eye, and making only the yellow spiral visible. A star also replaced the pupil to correspond with the celebrity series. The star also shone with a yellow glow.\n\n===Sponsorship===\nThe [[Carphone Warehouse]] remained as sponsor of the series, however due to highly publicised controversy which surrounded the series, Carphone Warehouse subsequently ended their long running association with Big Brother.\n\n===Broadcasts===\n[[Davina McCall]] presented the main Channel 4 show, including the live launch, evictions, finale and any other live show where a twist would take place. [[Marcus Bentley]] narrated the nightly highlight shows.\n\n[[Dermot O'Leary]] presented ''[[Big Brother's Little Brother|Celebrity Big Brother's Little Brother]]'' in a teatime slot weekdays and on Sunday lunchtime. He also presented ''[[Big Brother's Big Brain|Celebrity Big Brother's Big Brain]]'', which was introduced during [[Big Brother 7 (UK)|the previous non-celebrity series]], it would not return for any subsequent series.\n\nOn [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]], live coverage from the house once again dominated its daily and nightly schedule, [[E4 Music]] was once again rested during the series. [[Diary Room Uncut]] returned on Monday evenings and on Saturday night, straight after the Channel 4 show.\n\n[[Russell Brand]] presented ''[[Big Brother's Big Mouth|Celebrity Big Brother's Big Mouth]]'', which was broadcast Sunday to Friday straight after the Channel 4 show. Although no announcement was made during the series, Brand announced his departure on 4 April 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6526833.stm|title=Entertainment \u2013 Brand quits Big Brother spin-off|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nLive streaming also returned on the Official Channel 4 website and also on [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] at selected times.<ref>\"[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/bbbb/index.jsp Celebrity Big Brother's Big Brain]\", ''Channel 4's official Big Brother site''. Retrieved 4 January 2007.</ref>\n\n==House==\n[[File:CBB 2007 UK houseplan light.svg|thumb|right|House plan with the ''House Next Door'' highlighted.]]\nThe general layout of the House was largely untouched from the [[Big Brother 2006 (UK)|previous non-celebrity series]]. The living room and bedroom had no noticeable changes. There were several single beds in the same room, with one double bed, meaning that two housemates (Leo and Donny) had to share. The bathroom is much smaller than previous versions and the toilet and shower were no longer fitted with cameras. The dining room table was moved inside, and the kitchen fully equipped with modern conveniences. Outside the garden was a three-jet hot tub with a farmyard seating area. The bridge to Nowhere was still present, leading to a sitting area with heated seats and the [[topiary]] man. A workout area was situated just off the kitchen area. Inside the House there was also a fax machine built into the wall. On day 24 this was used to post viewers' questions to the housemates.<ref name=\"Questions,Questions\">{{cite url|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1428|title=Questions, Questions|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023015716/http://channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/B/bb7_celebrity/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1428&articleMask=1&housemateId=|date=2007-01-27|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|archive-date=23 October 2007|accessdate=2018-04-08|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Meanwhile, the Diary Room was identical to the previous summer's Big Brother, with an oversized gold chair and padded walls, the only change being the addition of yellow lights facing the walls.\n\n===House Next Door===\nThe House Next Door was used again, and its interior was re-designed to resemble a [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] style kitchen, with uncomfortable beds in the bedroom, for use in the master-and-servant task.\n\n==Housemates==\nEleven housemates entered the House on Day 1, followed by three more housemates on Day 3. This was more than any other celebrity series at the time.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; line-height:20px; width:auto;\" \n!scope=\"col\" | Celebrity\n!scope=\"col\" | Age on entry\n!scope=\"col\" | Notability\n!scope=\"col\" | Day entered\n!scope=\"col\" | Day exited\n!scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Shilpa Shetty]]\n| align=\"center\" | 31\n| [[Bollywood]] actress\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{won|Winner}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Jermaine Jackson]]\n| align=\"center\" | 52\n| [[The Jacksons (musical family)|Jackson family]] member and singer\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{Runner-up}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Dirk Benedict]]\n| align=\"center\" | 61\n| Actor\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{CFinalist|3rd Place}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Ian \"H\" Watkins]]\n| align=\"center\" | 30\n| Singer\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{CFinalist|4th Place}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Danielle Lloyd]]\n| align=\"center\" | 23\n| Glamour model and [[Miss Great Britain]]\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{CFinalist|5th Place}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Jack Tweed\n| align=\"center\" | 19\n| Boyfriend of Jade Goody\n| align=\"center\" | 3\n| align=\"center\" | 26\n| {{CFinalist|6th Place}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Cleo Rocos]]\n| align=\"center\" | 44\n| Actress\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n| align=\"center\" | 