[[Africa]].\n|-\n|{{sort|30|January 12, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Brazil|1889}}\n|[[Bel\u00e9m]]\n|-\n|{{sort|31|January 13, 1943}}\n|{{flagicon|Gambia|colonial}} [[The Gambia]]\n|[[Banjul|Bathurst]]\t\n|-\n|{{sort|32|January 14\u201325, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Morocco}}\n|[[Casablanca]]\n|Attended [[Casablanca Conference]] with British Prime Minister Winston Churchill.\n|-\n|{{sort|33|January 25, 1943}}\n|{{flagicon|Gambia|colonial}} [[The Gambia]]\n|Bathurst\n|Overnight stop en route from Casablanca.\n|-\n|{{sort|34|January 26\u201327, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Liberia}}\n|[[Monrovia]]\n|Informal visit. Met with President [[Edwin Barclay]].\n|-\n|{{sort|35|January 28, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Brazil|1889}}\n|[[Natal, Rio Grande do Norte|Natal]]\n|Informal visit. Met with President [[Get\u00falio Vargas]].\n|-\n|{{sort|36|January 29, 1943}}\n|{{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago|colonial}} [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n|Port of Spain\n|Overnight stop en route from Casablanca.\n|-\n|17\n|{{sort|37|April 20, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Mexico|1934}}\n|[[Monterrey]]\n| Part of an exchange of visits with President [[Manuel \u00c1vila Camacho]] across the border.\n|-\n|18\n|{{sort|38|August 17\u201325, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Canada|1921}}\n|Quebec City<br />[[Ottawa]]\n|Attended First [[Quebec Conference, 1943|Quebec Conference]] with Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill. Addressed senators, Members of Parliament, and the general public outside the houses of parliament.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/ParlInfo/compilations/parliament/HeadsOfStatesAddress.aspx| author=Parliament of Canada| title=Heads of States and of Governments who have addressed Joint Sessions of the Senate and House of Commons of Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=9|19\n|{{sort|39|November 20\u201321, 1943}}\n|{{sort|Alg|{{flagicon|France}} [[Algeria]]}}\n|[[Oran]]\n|Disembarked.\n|-\n|{{sort|40|November 21\u201322, 1943}}\n|{{sort|Tun|{{flagicon|France}} [[Tunisia]]}}\n|[[Tunis]]\n|Overnight stop.\n|-\n|{{sort|41|November 22\u201326, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Egypt|1922}}\n|[[Cairo]]\n| Attended First [[Cairo Conference]] with British Prime Minister Winston Churchill and Chinese leader [[Chiang Kai-shek]].\n|-\n|{{sort|42|November 27 \u2013 <br />December 2, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Iran|1925}}\n|[[Tehran]]\n|Attended [[Tehran Conference]] with Soviet Premier [[Joseph Stalin]] and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill.\n|-\n|{{sort|43|December 2\u20137, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Egypt|1922}}\n|Cairo\n|Attended [[Second Cairo Conference]] with British Prime Minister Winston Churchill and Turkish President [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]].\n|-\n|{{sort|44|December 7\u20139, 1943}}\n|{{sort|Tun|{{flagicon|France}} [[Tunisia]]}}\n|Tunis\n|Conferred with [[Military career of Dwight D. Eisenhower#World War II|General Dwight Eisenhower]].\n|-\n|{{sort|45|December 8, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Malta|1943}}\n|[[Valletta]]\n|Visited [[Fortifications of Malta#British fortifications (1800\u20131979)|Allied military installations]]\n|-\n|{{sort|46|December 8, 1943}}\n|{{flag|Italy|1861}}\n|[[Castelvetrano]]\n|Visited Allied military installations\n|-\n|{{sort|47|December 9, 1943}}\n|{{sort|Sen|{{flagicon|France}} [[Senegal]]}}\n|[[Dakar]]\n|Re-embarked for the U.S.\n|-\n|20\n|{{sort|48|September 11\u201316, 1944}}\n|{{flag|Canada|1921}}\n|Quebec City\n|Attended [[Second Quebec Conference]] with British Prime Minister Winston Churchill and the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[Combined Chiefs of Staff]].\n|-\n|rowspan=4|21\n|{{sort|49|February 2, 1945}}\n|{{flag|Malta|1943}}\n|[[Floriana]]\n|Attended [[Malta Conference (1945)|Malta Conference]] with Prime Minister Winston Churchill.\n|-\t\n|{{sort|50|February 3\u201312, 1945}}\n|{{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|[[Yalta]]\n|Attended [[Yalta Conference]] with Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill.\n|-\t\n|{{sort|51|February 13\u201315, 1945}}\n|{{flag|Egypt|1922}}\n|[[Great Bitter Lake]],<br />[[Suez Canal]],<br />[[Alexandria]]\n|Met with King [[Farouk of Egypt|Farouk]], Ethiopian Emperor [[Haile Selassie]], Saudi Arabian King [[Ibn Saud]], and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill.\n|-\n|{{sort|52|February 18, 1945}}\n|{{sort|Alg|{{flagicon|France}} [[Algeria]]}}\n|[[Algiers]]\n|Briefed [[Ambassadors of the United States|U.S. Ambassadors]] to the United Kingdom, France, and Italy on the Yalta Conference.\n|}\n\n==Election of 1940==\n{{Main|United States presidential election, 1940}}\n[[File:ElectoralCollege1940.svg|right|thumb|275px|1940 electoral vote results]]\nThe two-term tradition had been an unwritten rule (until the ratification the [[Twenty-second Amendment to the United States Constitution|22nd Amendment]] after Roosevelt's presidency) since George Washington declined to run for a third term in 1796. Both [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and [[Theodore Roosevelt]] were attacked for trying to obtain a third non-consecutive term. Roosevelt systematically undercut prominent Democrats who were angling for the nomination, including Vice President John Nance Garner<ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Robert Caro |last=Caro |first=Robert A. | series =[[The Years of Lyndon Johnson]] | title = The Path to Power | year = 1982 | publisher = [[Alfred A. Knopf, Inc.|Alfred A Knopf]] | location = [[New York City|New York]] | isbn = 0-394-49973-5 | pages = 578\u201381}}</ref> and two cabinet members, Secretary of State Hull and Postmaster General James Farley. Roosevelt moved the convention to Chicago where he had strong support from the city machine, which controlled the auditorium sound system. At the convention the opposition was poorly organized, but Farley had packed the galleries. Roosevelt sent a message saying that he would not run unless he was drafted, and that the delegates were free to vote for anyone. The delegates were stunned; then the loudspeaker screamed \"We want Roosevelt... The world wants Roosevelt!\" The delegates went wild and he was nominated by 946 to 147 on the first ballot. The tactic employed by Roosevelt was not entirely successful, as his goal had been to be drafted by acclamation.{{Sfn | Burns | 1956 | p = 428}} At Roosevelt's request, the convention nominated Secretary of Agriculture Henry Wallace for vice president. Democratic party leaders disliked Wallace, a former Republican who strongly supported the New Deal, but were unable to prevent his nomination.{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=457\u2013458}}\n\nWorld War II shook up the Republican field, possibly preventing the nomination of isolationist congressional leaders like Taft or Vandenberg. The [[1940 Republican National Convention]] instead nominated [[Wendell Willkie]], the first major party nominee since [[1872 United States presidential election|1872]] who had never held public office. A well-known corporate attorney and executive, Willkie rose to public notice through his criticism of the New Deal and his clashes with the TVA. Unlike his isolationist rivals for the Republican nomination, Willkie favored Britain in the war, and he was backed by internationalist Republicans like [[Henry Luce]].{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=455\u2013456}} Willkie's internationalist views initially prevented the issue of foreign policy from dominating the campaign, helping to allow for the Destroyers for Bases Agreement and the establishment of a peacetime draft.{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=459\u2013460}}\n\nAs the campaign drew to a close, Willkie and other Republicans stepped up their attacks on Roosevelt's foreign policy. Willkie warned that Roosevelt's re-election would lead to the deployment of U.S. troops abroad. In response, Roosevelt stated that \"Your boys are not going to be sent into any foreign wars.\"{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=462\u2013463}} Roosevelt won the [[1940 United States presidential election|1940 election]] with 55% of the popular vote and almost 85% of the electoral vote (449 to 82).{{Sfn | Burns | 1956 | p = 454}} Willkie won ten states: strongly Republican states of Vermont and Maine, and eight isolationist states in the Midwest.{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=463\u2013464}} The Democrats retained their congressional majorities, but the conservative coalition largely controlled domestic legislation and remained \"leery of presidential extensions of executive power through social programs.\"<ref>{{cite book |editor=Paul Finkelman |editor2=Peter Wallenstein |title=The encyclopedia of American political history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1IYYAAAAIAAJ|year=2001|publisher=CQ Press|page=332|isbn=9781568025117 }}</ref>\n\nAfter his victory over Willkie, Roosevelt embarked on a public campaign to win congressional support for aid to the British.{{Sfn|Herring|2008|pp=524\u2013525}} In December 1940, Roosevelt received a letter from Churchill asking the U.S. to repeal the cash and carry provision of the Neutrality Act. With British forces committed to defending against Germany, Churchill asked for the United States to provide loans and shipping for American goods.{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=467\u2013468}} In response, Roosevelt delivered a speech in which he called for the United States to serve as the \"[[Arsenal of Democracy]],\" supplying aid to those resisting Germany and other aggressors.{{Sfn|Herring|2008|pp=524\u2013525}} He stated, \"if Great Britain goes down, the Axis Powers will control the continents of Europe, Asia, Africa, Australasia, and the high seas\u2013and they will be in a position to bring enormous military military and naval resources against this hemisphere.\"{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=401\u2013402}} In his January 1941 [[Four Freedoms]] speech, Roosevelt laid out the case for an American defense of basic rights throughout the world.{{sfn|Smith|2007|pp=487\u2013488}} In that same speech, Roosevelt asked Congress to approve a [[Lend-Lease]] program designed to provide military aid to Britain.{{sfn|Kennedy|1999|pp=469\u2013470}} Roosevelt's [[Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt, third and fourth terms|third term]] subsequently began on January 20, 1941, and would see a continuation of many of his policies.\n\n==Historical reputation==\n{{Further|Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt, third and fourth terms#Historical reputation}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Causes of the Great Depression]]\n*[[Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*[[Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt, third and fourth terms|Third and fourth terms of the presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Alter | first = Jonathan | author-link = Jonathan Alter| year = 2006 | title = The Defining Moment: FDR's Hundred Days and the Triumph of Hope | isbn = 978-0-7432-4600-2 | type = popular history}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Black | first = Conrad | author-link = Conrad Black| year = 2005 | origyear = 2003 | title = Franklin Delano Roosevelt: Champion of Freedom |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lYVCi70HaigC | isbn = 9781586482824 }}  1276pp interpretive detailed biography\n* {{Cite book | author-link = H. W. Brands| last = Brands | first = HW | title = Traitor to His Class: The Privileged Life and Radical Presidency of Franklin Delano Roosevelt | year = 2009 }}\n* {{cite book |ref= harv |last= Burns |first=James MacGregor | year= 1956 | title= Roosevelt: The Lion and the Fox|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.87676}} scholarly biography to 1940; [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.87676 online].\n* {{cite book | last = Burns | first = James MacGregor | title = Roosevelt: The Soldier of Freedom | url = https://archive.org/details/rooseveltsoldier0000burn | url-access = registration | publisher = Harcourt Brace Jovanovich | location = San Diego | year = 1970 | isbn = 978-0-15-178871-2}}\n* {{cite book |ref=Churchill |last=Churchill |first=Winston |authorlink=Winston Churchill |title=The Grand Alliance |year=1977 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn = 0-395-41057-6|title-link=The Second World